                <ns5:provenance xml:lang="en">…; ? Wittevrouwenklooster, Haarlem;{Van Luttervelt 1948, pp. 265-68.} ? inventory, Commandery of St John, 1572, the small office (‘Tauoreel vanden boom van Iesse’), or in the salon (‘Tauoreel gechiert vanden boom van Iesse’);{Van Bueren 1993, pp. 394-96, 494-96.} ? inventory, Commandery of St John, Adriaensdoelen, Haarlem, 1573, the upper room with wainscotting (‘Tauoreel sonder deuren vanden boom van Iesse’);{Van Bueren 1993, pp. 395, 515.} …; Kvovinsky, St Petersburg, c. 1850;{Note RMA.} …; Demidoff, St Petersburg [possibly Paul Demidoff (1839-85)];{Note RMA.} …; sale, Chevalier F. Meazza (Milan), sold on the premises (Riblet), 15 (21) April 1884 &lt;em&gt;sqq.&lt;/em&gt;, no. 200, as Quinten Massijs; …; Count Grégoire S. Stroganoff (? -1910), Palazzo Stroganoff, Rome, as Geertgen, 1907;{Dülberg III, 1907, p. 8.} from whom purchased by the dealer Charles Albert de Burlet, c. 1923-24;{Note RMA.} from whom purchased by Catalina von Pannwitz (1876-1959), De Hartekamp, Heemstede, as Jan Mostaert, 1926;{Coll. cat. Von Pannwitz 1925-26, p. 3, no. 14, plate VIII.} from whom, as Geertgen, through the dealer S. Rosenberg, New York, $ 58,000 (approx. fl. 211,000) to the museum, with support from the Vereniging Rembrandt, 1956</ns5:provenance>
